  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible experience that affects how people perform, especially when they're from underrepresented groups. Having grown up in a small town where my parents' educational backgrounds were quite different—my father with a PhD and my mother with a vocational diploma—I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape expectations. For instance, when I was in high school, I remember a classmate who was the first in her family to go to college and was initially discouraged from pursuing engineering because she was told, 'You're not built for that.' That comment, though seemingly small, had a profound impact on her confidence. Stereotype threat manifests when individuals internalize negative stereotypes about their group, leading to anxiety that hinders their performance. In my own experience as a barista, I've noticed how people often hesitate to engage with STEM topics when they feel judged by others' expectations. Should we address it? Absolutely. The solution isn't about changing the system overnight but about creating environments where everyone feels safe to explore their interests without fear of being labeled. This means starting with simple gestures—like ensuring that classrooms and workplaces have diverse role models and inclusive language. I've found that in my yoga classes, when we talk about mental health and self-acceptance, it helps people feel more comfortable expressing their doubts. Addressing stereotype threat requires patience, empathy, and a commitment to listening. It's not about fixing people but about fixing the environment so they can thrive. After all, in a world that often feels overwhelming, especially for those who are anxious, it's crucial to create spaces where everyone can be their authentic selves without fear.",
